<DOC><DOCNO> AP880726-0077 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-88 1001EDT</FILEID><FIRST>d a PM-NitroCoffee     07-26 0178</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Nitro Coffee,0183</SECOND><HEAD>Grandson Arrested For Investigation In Coffee Tampering Case</HEAD><DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The grandson of an elderly woman who foundnitroglycerin tablets in her coffee has been arrested forinvestigation of attempted murder, police said.   Alfred Sevilla, 23, was arrested Monday after numerousinconsistencies in his story to detectives surfaced, said policeLt. Sergio Robleto.   Before the arrest, however, a market in the woman's eastsideneighborhood, which had sold her the coffee, pulled it from theshelves. The brand was removed after police contacted the store,which was not identified, and said there was a possibility theproduct had been contaminated.   Sevilla's grandmother, Irma Rangel, 67, reported findingcrushed, broken and whole white pills in a coffee jar when shestarted preparing a cup on Friday, Robleto said.   Lab tests of the pills revealed they matched those from aprescription vial of nitroglycerin in Ms. Rangel's home, Robletosaid.   No one in the household suffered any ill effects, Robleto said.   Nitroglycerin is often prescribed to heart patients to dilateblood vessels that become constricted.</TEXT></DOC>